Coccinia grandis

fruits (547 fruits; 
7.53 kg
) were collected during 
1994 to 1999 in
the

Nui, Makiki, and Waimanalo) from 
December 1988
to 
April 1989
and from two sites on the Island of 
Hawaii
(Kailua and Kalaoa) on 
21–22 April 1989
. Fruits were held in wooden frames with screen bottoms lined with newspaper, placed in fiberglass boxes with a layer of fine vermiculite on the bottom. Vermiculite was screened weekly with recovered larvae and pupae transferred to paper packages for adult emergence. Adult 

B. cucurbitae

recoveries were 254.6 flies/kg fruit (Ewa; 84 fruits; 
1.0959 kg
), 73.0 flies/kg fruit (Kamilo Nui; 7 fruits; 
0.0685 kg
), 0.0 flies/kg fruit (Makiki; 3 fruits; 
0.0775 kg
), 54.5 flies/kg fruit (Waimanalo; 124 fruits; 
2.1463 kg
), 0.0 flies/kg fruit (Kailua; 36 fruits; 
0.3799 kg
), and 0.0 flies/kg fruit (Kalaoa; 7 fruits; 
0.1156 kg
).

